.planning\research\CONSULT-17-08-gap6-tangent-basis-codex.out:136:Specifically: make the D3D11 
plugin prove whether every `TEXCOORDn` in the compiled VS input signature is backed by a real vertex 
declaration element before assigning it to the phantom zero slot. If `TEXCOORD2` is present in the 
actual vertex declaration or secondary stream, it must bind to the real VB offset/slot. Only truly 
absent inputs should be phantom-filled.
.planning\research\CONSULT-17-08-gap6-tangent-basis-codex.out:202:My expectation: D3D9 will show a 
real `TEXCOORD2` or equivalent stream for the bump draw. Character meshes with bump/specular skin 
generally need a tangent frame somewhere.
.planning\research\CONSULT-17-08-gap6-tangent-basis-codex.out:222:- Secondary stream or 
instanced/extra stream is not bound in D3D11.
.planning\research\CONSULT-17-08-gap6-tangent-basis-codex.out:276:But for real parity, if D3D9 also 
lacked the stream and still rendered correctly, you need to identify the original derivation path. 
It may have used a different texcoord, a pretransformed basis, or shader bytecode that did not match 
the recompiled source path.
.planning\research\CONSULT-17-08-gap6-tangent-basis-codex.out:287:   - Bound VB stride and stream 
slot.
.planning\research\CONSULT-17-08-gap6-tangent-basis-codex.out:319:- **Secondary stream missing.** 
Tangent basis may be in a second stream that D3D9 bound but D3D11 does not.
.planning\research\CONSULT-17-08-gap6-tangent-basis-codex.out:320:- **Skinning path mismatch.** For 
skinned meshes, tangent/binormal must be skinned with the same weights as normal. If the tangent 
exists but is not skinned or is read from the wrong stream, lighting will still be wrong, though 
usually not all-zero.
.planning\research\CONSULT-17-08-gap6-tangent-basis-codex.out:350:3. **Bind missing secondary 
streams if present.**
.planning\research\CONSULT-17-08-gap6-tangent-basis-codex.out:352:If the D3D9 declaration references 
stream `1+`, the D3D11 path must bind the corresponding VB slot with the correct stride and offset. 
A phantom should only be used when the declaration truly lacks the semantic/index.
