.planning\research\CONSULT-19-d3d11-world-corruption-ROUND2-codex.out:4368:If latched corruption 
survives live but every captured Present is clean, capture instrumentation is masking the producer. 
If you ever capture the latched-corrupt backbuffer and replay is corrupt, it is in-stream and you 
should use pixel history/resource inspection.
.planning\research\CONSULT-19-d3d11-world-corruption-ROUND2-codex.out:4471:If latched corruption 
survives live but every captured Present is clean, capture instrumentation is masking the producer. 
If you ever capture the latched-corrupt backbuffer and replay is corrupt, it is in-stream and you 
should use pixel history/resource inspection.
.planning\research\CONSULT-18-half-texel-seam.md:102:- **Path B — CPU-side NDC pre-conversion** of 
the transformed vertex stream, near
.planning\research\CONSULT-19-d3d11-world-corruption-ROUND2-cursor.out:15:| **C. Replay 
rehydration** | Recorded stream + serialized initial contents reproduce a good image even when live 
GPU memory at record time was wrong (less likely if export-at-Present is truly from replayed 
commands, not a live readback). |
.planning\research\CONSULT-19-d3d11-world-corruption-ROUND2-cursor.out:59:**Why TEST 3 (Flush + 
event after `Present`) may not kill it:** you only drain the GPU **between frames**. Hazards are 
**within** one frame’s command stream. By Present, the GPU has consumed the corrupted composition; 
replay of that same stream should still look corrupt — **unless** you captured a clean frame (branch 
A).
.planning\research\CONSULT-19-d3d11-world-corruption-ROUND2-cursor.out:97:**Why LOD/distance:** 
streaming tiles / impostors / far LODs are exactly “create → bind early → upload late.”
.planning\research\CONSULT-19-d3d11-world-corruption-ROUND2-cursor.out:134:| Replay Present 
**corrupt**, SRV texels **wrong** | In-stream content/upload bug (not timing). |
.planning\research\CONSULT-19-d3d11-world-corruption-ROUND2-cursor.out:136:| Replay Present 
**clean**, live latched corrupt | Frame mismatch **or** display path (A/B), not hidden GPU stream. |
.planning\research\CONSULT-19-d3d11-world-corruption-ROUND2-cursor.out:147:2. **Draw before texture 
upload completes** (1c) — explains “whole surface wrong recognizable texture” on streamed LODs; 
async loader off doesn’t force synchronous **GPU** upload before first draw on the render thread.
.planning\research\CONSULT-19-d3d11-world-corruption-ROUND2-cursor.out:186:| **Display scanout / 
flip / MPO / fullscreen optimizations** | 3, 5, 8 | GPU stream clean; monitor wrong. Flip model: 
`DXGI_SWAP_EFFECT_FLIP_DISCARD`, 2 buffers. |
.planning\research\CONSULT-19-d3d11-world-corruption-ROUND2-cursor.out:199:1. **TEST 8 is the 
anchor.** Clean Present export is hard to reconcile with “the recorded stream is wrong but replay 
fixes it.” It pushes you toward **A (wrong frame)** or **B (display path)** before **GPU Heisenbug**.
.planning\research\CONSULT-19-d3d11-world-corruption-cursor.out:118:If replay of the **same corrupt 
capture** produces a fully correct image, that is **not** consistent with “draw stream is fine but 
every bound texture is random VRAM.” RenderDoc would replay the same garbage unless it substitutes 
zeros (which tends to look black/flat, not correct stone buildings).
.planning\research\CONSULT-19-d3d11-world-corruption-cursor.out:144:| **Async loader** | Rules out 
loader thread races, not “texture created → SRV bindable → first draw before `load()` finishes” on 
the main thread if the engine allows that for streaming LOD. |
