.planning\research\CONSULT-22-REVIEW-codex.out:5194:   Original Ã¢â‚¬Å“capture replays cleanÃ¢â‚¬Â 
fits async CPU/GPU reuse. Per-generation Ã¢â‚¬Å“capture replays dirtyÃ¢â‚¬Â means the dirty bytes 
existed in the submitted stream RenderDoc captured. That usually indicates the new code made 
corruption deterministic before capture: wrong generation bound, generation reused before deferred 
draw, offset/accounting bug, or data uploaded into one resource while draw reads another. It does 
not exonerate the original race; it says the attempted fix introduced or exposed a separate 
deterministic lifetime/binding failure.
.planning\research\CONSULT-22-REVIEW-codex.out:5203:2. Yes, the capture-invisible to 
capture-deterministic transition is key. It strongly suggests the per-generation patch was not a 
correct fix. It likely made a concrete stale-buffer/stale-offset/reused-generation state visible in 
the captured command stream.
.planning\research\CONSULT-22-REVIEW-codex.out:5209:5. Minimal correct fix I would choose: **isolate 
soft-skin positions from the shared UI ring**. Give soft-skinned primitives their own D3D11 dynamic 
buffer or small per-primitive/per-frame buffer set, bind offset 0, update with `WRITE_DISCARD`, and 
do not remap that primitiveÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s soft-skin buffer again until the next skin update. Keep 
`CuiLayerRenderer` on the shared ring. This matches the RenderDoc evidence: only soft-skin POSITION 
stream is bad, while UIÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s lock-all behavior is an accidental rename pump, not a design to 
preserve.
