.planning\research\CONSULT-19-d3d11-world-corruption-codex.out:2506:One important D3D11-only 
asymmetry surfaced: static VB/IB `lockReadOnly()` does not read back existing contents in gl11; it 
returns zeroed CPU memory. D3D9 returns the actual buffer. That is a credible geometry-corruption 
source in any path that derives/streams/rebuilds LOD data from already-created buffers, but it does 
not directly explain recognizable wrong texture content.
.planning\research\CONSULT-19-d3d11-world-corruption-codex.out:2727:Why: near geometry is fine, 
mid/far corrupt, and surfaces show recognizable other-asset content. That screams: correct SRV, 
correct shader, correct base mip, but the sampler chooses an uninitialized lower mip. RenderDoc 
replay-clean is especially consistent with this because the captured command stream can be correct 
while live undefined resource memory contains stale VRAM; replay tools often sanitize or reconstruct 
missing resource content.
.planning\research\CONSULT-19-d3d11-world-corruption-codex.out:2760:Why: near geometry is fine, 
mid/far corrupt, and surfaces show recognizable other-asset content. That screams: correct SRV, 
correct shader, correct base mip, but the sampler chooses an uninitialized lower mip. RenderDoc 
replay-clean is especially consistent with this because the captured command stream can be correct 
while live undefined resource memory contains stale VRAM; replay tools often sanitize or reconstruct 
missing resource content.
