.planning\research\CONSULT-31-codex.out:513:**Why D3D11-ONLY (the reconciliation we were missing):** 
this skin code is SHARED, but the **meshâ†’primitive-class choice upstream differs** â€” D3D11 
routes these robes through `SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive` (SM_softSkinning, CPU, runs this 
buggy loop); D3D9 hardware-skins them (GPU), never executing `fillVertexBuffer`. So the latent 
OOB-index bug only fires under D3D11.
.planning\research\CONSULT-31-codex.out:567:- **Cursor 30** (`CONSULT-30-cursor.out`): NO unwritten 
declared vertex component. Single-stream `dynamicFormat` = position+normal(+color+UVs+dot3); 
`skinData` writes position/normal/dot3 each frame, `fillConstantVertexBufferData` writes 
color/2D-UVs once; copy is full-vertex memcpy â†’ every declared byte populated at draw. 
Input-layout offsets/stride match engine exactly. VS uses POSITION-only for SV_Position. â†’ REFUTES 
"VS reads an unwritten component." Points to **index read-past (whole stale vertices)** or **"GPU 
sees different memory than the CPU staging read"** (coherency/ring-timing).
.planning\research\CONSULT-31-codex.out:573:Top ranks recycled already-killed ideas (strip=dormant, 
multi-stream=off, systemStream-uninit would be captured-not-zeroed). Two FRESH + fitting: **(Rank 5) 
STALE CACHED InputLayout stride mismatch** â€” IA stride 48 vs a cached layout expecting 32 â†’ 
verts read N bytes off, position-at-0 still correct (fits "position clean"); Cursor 30 only checked 
the CURRENT format, not a stale cached layout â€” WORTH CHECKING the input-layout cache key/stride 
at garment draws. **(Rank 7) `getRingBuffer()` NULL-fallback to MAIN ring** if a garment binds 
before its first lock (m_ringBuffer==nullptr) â€” a risk introduced by the 16MB skin-ring split; 
reverting the skin ring removes it. Full: `CONSULT-30-SONNET-lateral.out`.
.planning\research\CONSULT-31-codex.out:619:3. **The bound offset at the draw is CORRECT.** SBSSP 
binds via the VECTOR path (`setVertexBuffer(*m_vertexBufferVector)` â†’ 
`ms_currentVBVectorOffsets[0]`, NOT single-stream). After a rebind-at-draw fix, the draw's bound 
offset matches the write offset exactly. â†’ not a stale/clobbered bind. (The rebind fix DID NOT 
stop the spike â†’ bind was never the cause.)
